10-24 West 49th Street, south side, west of Fifth Avenue, as seen across Rockefeller Plaza. New 45-story building under construction is a unit of Radio City and is located at 16 to 24 West 49th Street; the other numbers being the three, fourstory buildings adjoining on the 'ifth Avenue side. On the extreme left is the rear of the French Building, another unit. The lower stories of the 70 storied R.C.A. Building appears on
the extreme right.
1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Writers Project.

723028f.text:
Fifth Ave., between West 46th (left) and 52nd (rimht) Streets, and showing mainly Rockefeller Center and westward to the Hudson River as seen from No. 444 Madison Ave. In the foreground appears the roof of Saks Department Store with the spires of St. Patrick's adjoining. Units of the afore mentioned Radio City are, La Maison Francaise, British Empire Building, 45 storied International Building, 31 storied R.K.O. Building (8 storied International Music Hall at its rear), 70 storied R.C.A. Building and the 8 storied R.E.O. Theatre (also known as Roxy's and Center).
1936.
W.P.A. Photo.

(1)
49th Street, west from Fifth Avenue, showing the houses along "Speakeasy Row." During prohibition, most of these houses were illegal saloons. One resident in this neighborhood was compelled to place over his doorbell a card reading "Private House," to avoid being awakened at any hour by thirsty revellers. All of these houses are now gone, and the site occupied by Rockefeller Centre.
August 18, 1929.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, a year earlier, and not including Fifth Avenue.
May 6, 1928.

731255f-a.title: Celebrations - Parades - Municipal events - Murphy Funeral.
731255f-a.text:
Celebrations, Parades and Municipal Events: A set of three views of the funeral procession of Chas. Francis Murphy, former leader of Tammany Hall, approaching St. Patrick's Cathedral. This individual died at his home at 305 East 17th Street, on April 26, 1924 and this last mass was held April 29, prior to interment in old Calvary Cemetery. In No's 1 and 2 the view is southward on Fifth Ave., across 49th Street and northward in No. 3. For an account of this occurence and the life of the individual,
see,the New York Times of April 26 to 29, 1924.
April 29, 1924.
